From `EditorSettings::create`:

```
    if (OS::get_singleton()->has_environment("APPDATA")) {
        // Most likely under windows, save here
        config_path=OS::get_singleton()->get_environment("APPDATA");
        config_dir=String(_MKSTR(VERSION_SHORT_NAME)).capitalize();
    } else if (OS::get_singleton()->has_environment("HOME")) {

        config_path=OS::get_singleton()->get_environment("HOME");
        config_dir="."+String(_MKSTR(VERSION_SHORT_NAME)).to_lower();
    }
```

The settings directory is decided and created here and the `OS` class has no way to set a custom settings directory.
I am working on the Haiku port and there we do not use `~/.appname` for storing settings but `~/config/settings/appname`.

So my proposal is to add an `OS::get_settings_dir` method and use it in `EditorSettings::create`.

I'm trying to get an external module working but have issues with functions using const char*. In the module i need to send and receive text to an external DLL library which source code I do not have access to. When compiling the module together with Godot I run into some issues.

I have made a tiny example module below to demonstrate the issues. See comments in the code.

``` c++
/* chartest.h */
#ifndef CHARTEST_H
#define CHARTEST_H

#include "reference.h"

class Chartest : public Reference {
    OBJ_TYPE(Chartest,Reference);

protected:
    static void _bind_methods();
public:
    const char* getString(); // compiles ok, but Godot crashes on startup

    int putString(const char* str); // causes compilation error:
    // e:\godot-2.0-beta\core\method_bind.h(61): error C2440: 'return' : cannot convert from 'const Variant' to 'const char *'
    // No user-defined-conversion operator available that can perform this conversion, or the operator cannot be called

    Chartest();
};

#endif
```

``` c++
/* chartest.cpp */

#include "chartest.h"

Chartest::Chartest() {
}

void Chartest::_bind_methods() {
    ObjectTypeDB::bind_method("getString",&Chartest::getString);
    ObjectTypeDB::bind_method("putString",&Chartest::putString);

}

const char* Chartest::getString(){
    return "a string";
}

int Chartest::putString(const char* str){
        return 0;
}
```

I have tried to use the Godot 'String' but when doing so the external DLL only receive the first letter in the text string I try to send.

What is the proper way to handle this? Implement functions in the Variant class to be able to handle const char\* or is there another/intended/better way to do what I'm trying to do here?

